If you create a 600 DPI image of a text page, you're, say, a 5 by 7 text page, you're creating something that has 5 times 600...
3,000 pixels by 4,200 pixels across.
Monitors, even high-resolution monitors, are only able to project around 1,200 pixels.
So if you're sending 4,000 pixels to the monitor, you're going to end up with only a small percent of the image being displayed.
And so if you were doing a 600 dpi to a common setting of a monitor, like 640 by 480 pixels,
you'd get less than 5% of the image displayed.
So what we do is we derive a use copy for display from the 600 dpi image itself.

We basically send a 100 dpi version to the screen, and we add some gray to it because they're using color monitors, and it's the kind of light that is transmitted light rather than reflected light, and it leads to better legibility.
